Matter can change its state by receiving or releasing energy. For example, if you warm up ice it will melt or if you heat up water it will boil. Solids can become liquids and they can even become gas. In the same way, liquids can become gas and gas can produce liquids. All these changes of state have a very specific name. You might be familiar with some of them such as melting, which refers to the change from a solid to a liquid, or freezing which refers to the change from a liquid to a solid. The freezing and melting point of a pure substance are exactly the same and substances have unique freezing (or melting) point. For example, water freezes and melts at 0$^{\circ}C$. Other changes of state are less well known, and vaporization refers to the change from a liquid to a gas, whereas condensation refers to the change from a gas to a liquid. Sublimation refers to the change from a solid to a gas, whereas deposition refers to the change from a gas to a solid.

